<DOC><DOCNO> AP890106-0210 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 0127EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   01-06 0474</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0495</SECOND><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Retailers who expected only a modest pickup in their Christmasbusiness got a big _ and welcome _ surprise as consumers, caught upin the holiday spirit, shopped with renewed enthusiasm in December.   Analysts said Thursday that holiday sales were higher thanexpected, rising in a range of 6 percent to 7.5 percent, animprovement over the 6 percent gain forecast before the start of theseason.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Booming year-end car and truck sales at GeneralMotors Corp. and a jump in car sales at Ford Motor Co. contributedto an overall increase in domestic sales of cars and light trucks in1988.   Manufacturers said Thursday that sales of U.S.-made cars andlight trucks averaged 44,477 a day in the Dec. 21-31 period, up 20.7percent from the same period in 1987.   For the year, domestic car and light-truck sales reached 11.7million, averaging 38,060 a day in 1988, up 7.5 percent from 1987.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Toyota Motor Corp. will be allowed to keep thename of its new Lexus line of luxury cars, at least temporarily.   An appeals court in New York extended on Thursday a reprievegiven the company earlier this week after a federal judge issued arestraining order last week forbidding Toyota from using the Lexusname. It resumes hearings Jan. 30.   Mead Data General Inc. has sued Toyota claiming that the Lexusname diluted the business of its Lexis legal information retrievalservice.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Takeover speculator Paul Bilzerian pleadedinnocent to 12 counts of fraud and said he hoped to clear his nameand resume hunting for companies to buy.   The 38-year-old financier, who heads Singer Co., was arraignedThursday in Manhattan federal court on a dozen felony counts linkedto four failed takeover situations in 1985 and 1986.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s high-yield bondfinancier Michael Milken is facing unprecedented pressure to strikea plea deal with prosecutors after his firm agreed to expel him andwithhold his 1988 compensation as part of its settlement of criminalfraud charges.   Sources familiar with the negotiations Thursday confirmed pressreports about terms of a probable departure by Milken, who hascontinued to assert innocence in a deepening criminal investigationof his financial dealings.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A top lawyer defending GAF Corp. against stockmanipulation charges hammered away at the credibility of thegovernment's star witness, who admitted he'd discarded records thatdocumented the alleged crime.   Defense attorney Arthur Liman's grilling Thursday of formersecurities broker Boyd Jefferies dominated the latest session in thetrial of GAF and one of its senior officers, now in its third weekat Manhattan federal court.   GAF and vice chairman James Sherwin have vowed to vindicatethemselves.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>